<br>
Umm...  Try this:<br>
<br>
1.  Money is spent on National Defense in order to ::GASP:: DEFEND the NATION.  Although it is certainly true that some defense spending is motivated by other factors, again that is a by-product, not the primary purpose.  Furthermore, economic meddling that is done through the Aegis of National Defense is in itself contradictory to your position.  If the Purpose of the Government was to correct Market Failures, they would just do it without the cover of National Defense.<br>
<br>
2.  Taxes are levied so the Government can FUND the programs that it uses to run the Country and serve its citizens.  Pollution is NOT a Market Failure.  If anything, under a purely capitalistic model, it is a Market OPPORTUNITY.  Now you can create an industry to clean pollution.<br>
<br>
3.  Anti-Trust legislation exists because the US favors a capitalistic Free Market, that is correct.  It still does not make it the 'function' of Government.<br>
<br>
Any time there IS a Market Failure, the Government must DECIDE if it will do anything to attempt to corrct it or not (qv Economic Stimulus, Airline Bailout).  If you said the role of the FED was to correct Market Failures, I would agree without question.  But the scope of the US Government is far broader tha that.  Unless you think Afghanistan and Iraq are examples of &quot;Market Failure Correction.&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>  I'm not sure what else your looking for here, but I think that my response to your market failure question can be looked at to refute this second point you made as well, if I read you right. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
