<br>
I went back and reread the post you mentioned. Rather than ask me to shlog through that (and yes, I did shlog through the whole thing), please, insult me and make me look like an idiot.<br>
<br>
I still don't see how you can expect anyone else to arrive at your point 12 from the previous 11 points. It is a non sequitor.<br>
<br>
I agree that the music industry is seriously flawed, that record companies make disgusting profits from the work of the artists, and that the price one is required to pay for industry music is ridiculous. I do not see how this justifies theft. And that is what not paying for intellectual property is. On this point you'll not dissuade me.<br>
<br>
I read your link to Courtney Love's interpretation of the math of the music industry, and have only one problem with it. She represents it as happening to bands that are bid over by several labels. Any band, established enough to generate a bidding war by various labels, that allows this to happen to it, deserves it. A band like that should have the label paying for studio time, not themselves. A band like that should have the label paying for it's video under the promotion budget. A band like that should have the label not only paying the tour expeses, but getting paid for the tour. A band like that shouldn't recieve an &quot;advance&quot;, they should get a signing bonus. Change it to a band with marginal recognition that gets one and only one offer from a major label and I'd be much more likely to believe it. Even then, the devil doesn't force you to sell your soul, he just makes it look attractive in the short run. The artists accept these shitty contracts, and sign over their intellectual property to the record label on the hope of breaking big. They're not bad, or greedy, or idiots, just ambitious and maybe niave.<br>
<br>
I agree that there is a change coming to the music industry, and the major record labels aren't going to like it.<br>
<br>
None of this justifies theft.<br>
<br>
Good luck with the storm.<br>
<br>
Xethux<br>
